<p>The <a href="/wiki/English_language" >English</a> word "news" developed in the 14th century as a special use of the plural form of "new".<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> In <a href="/wiki/Middle_English" >Middle English</a>, the equivalent word was <i>newes</i>, like the French <i><a href="//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/nouvelles" class="extiw" >nouvelles</a></i> and the German <i>neues</i>. Similar developments are found in the <a href="/wiki/Slavic_languages" >Slavic languages</a> – the <a href="/wiki/Czech_language" >Czech</a> and <a href="/wiki/Slovak_language" >Slovak</a> <i><a href="//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/noviny" class="extiw" >noviny</a></i> (from <i><a href="//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/nov%C3%BD" class="extiw" >nový</a></i>, "new"), the <a href="/wiki/Cognate" >cognate</a> <a href="/wiki/Polish_language" >Polish</a> <i>nowiny</i> and <a href="/wiki/Russian_language" >Russian</a> <i>novosti</i> – and in the <a href="/wiki/Celtic_languages" >Celtic languages</a>: the <a href="/wiki/Welsh_language" >Welsh</a> <i>newyddion</i> (from <i>newydd</i>) and the <a href="/wiki/Cornish_language" >Cornish</a> <i>nowodhow</i> (from <i>nowydh</i>).</p>
